Description: Journalist's Resource surfaces research on today's news topics.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Boston Area, East Coast, New England
Full Description: Based at Harvard’s Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy, the Journalist’s Resource project examines news topics through a research lens. They surface scholarly materials that may be relevant to media practitioners, bloggers, educators, students and general readers. Their  philosophy is that peer-reviewed research studies can, at the very least, help anchor journalists as they navigate difficult terrain and competing claims. In 2013 the American Library Association named us one of the best free reference Web sites. Their weekly email and Twitter feed serve to highlight the latest studies from academia that can inform public discourse. Given the deluge of research output every day, they aim to be a useful curator. Their searchable database contains top academic and governmental research that they have selected and synthesized. They strive to translate complex statistics into clear data points and reformulate the terminology of academic specialists into more accessible language, without sacrificing rigor or nuance. While they can’t provide access to the full text of every study, they try to provide at least a point of entry and highlight key points — and they encourage media members to contact the authors of the research directly. We invite all those interested in policy and public affairs to use the site’s materials, in particular instructors, students and journalists. No registration is required; the materials are free and are under a Creative Commons license. To understand the site’s basic goals, we recommend that you read their primer: “Introduction to Studies and Academic Research: How It Works and Why Journalists Should Care.” Their project has partnered with the New York Times, for example, to help create more research-related resources for readers; other active partners include the Nieman Journalism Lab and Scholars Strategy Network at Harvard. We also foster the improvement of Wikipedia pages relating to policy topics.
Industry Groups: Content and Publishing, Education, Media and Entertainment, Other, Social Impact

Full Description: MetaSepia is an optical proximity transactions system for mobile devices, offering a ubiquitous offline mobile to online mobile payments extension. MetaSepia also offers an mobile offline to online merchant payments at the mPOS that is ubiquitous and unique in allowing direct mobile transactions at the online merchant cloud services. MetaSepia received project funding in 2019, and demonstrating mobile to mobile EMV payments, and online mobile payments. View a 2.39 second GooglePay EMV protocol payment on a certified test network here: https://youtu.be/nZ87OHUlOGI MetaSepia’s software-only products reside at the front-end of P2P and B2C mobile transactions for your proprietary wallet or ID verification app. We extend the online SaaS merchant directly to the offline retail customer mobile walle with the same security and payment protocols as online payments, and we enable offline to offline ubiquitous device  proximity payments with the same protocols as NFC-EMV. We use the front-facing cameras to analyze the screens on the mobile devices, enabling data sharing. The use of a merchant mPOS as a pass-through device enables secure Point2Point Encryption via typical TLS/SSL security, and the transaction is cloud-based.

Description: Online education web app (admissions)
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Apply in the Sky is an online platform, dedicated to providing technology-based solutions for those exploring next steps in education and career. The Company is the first to develop a SaaS-based solution to streamline the graduate school application process, starting with business schools (www.applyinthesky.com).   In September 2010, Apply in the Sky launched a web-based application that addresses key pain points in the MBA admissions process, addressing the significant time-management, work flow management and organizational challenges related to applying to multiple schools. Apply in the Sky's tools help applicants save time, stay organized, better aggregate the information and resources they need, understand how they stack up, and gain an edge in the the competitive MBA admissions process. The Company's ultimate goal is to be the go-to platform for those embarking on important next steps in education and career.
